The movement rates of caribou (corrected for individual and location frequency) were significantly higher on ice (1625 ± 51 m/h SE; 
 t = 31.95, df = 136 211, 
 P < 0.01) and during detours (994 ± 31 m/h SE; 
 t = 18.64, df = 136 163, 
 P < 0.01) than elsewhere in the study area (535 ± 2 m/h SE; Fig. 
 5a). Movement rates across water were not different from controls (643 ± 82 m/h SE; 
 t = 1.09, df = 136 146, 
 P = 0.27). The turning angle (absolute value: range 0–180°) of steps was higher in open water (70.3 ± 4.7° SE; 
 t = 2.14, df = 135 988, 
 P = 0.03) and lower across ice (33.9 ± 1.5° SE; 
 t = −11.23, df = 136 054, 
 P < 0.01) and detours (43.3 ± 1.3° SE; 
 t = −8.81, df = 136 006, 
 P < 0.01) compared to all other steps at similar dates (57.6 ± 0.1° SE; Fig. 
 5b).
